The cluster public key infrastructure, who has what certificate.

A kubernetes cluster is held together by tee-el-ess. Almost every component talks to almost every other component over h-t-t-p-s, and identities are proven with x five oh nine client certificates.

A kube-ay-dee-m cluster has two certificate authorities by default. The kubernetes certificate authority signs all the front end certificates, for the ay-pee-eye server, the kube-let clients, and so on. And the et-see-dee certificate authority signs et-see-dee's own server and peer certificates. There is also a third, the front proxy authority, used by the ay-pee-eye aggregation layer for extension ay-pee-eye servers, which has less day to day relevance.

The certificates themselves live under slash e-t-c slash kubernetes slash p-k-i. The ones to know are these. The ay-pee-eye server's own serving certificate. The ay-pee-eye server to kube-let client certificate. The ay-pee-eye server to et-see-dee client certificate. Et-see-dee's server and peer certificates. And the front proxy client certificate for the aggregation layer. Each is signed by one of the two authorities and proves one component's identity to another.

On top of that, each node's kube-let has its own client certificate. Modern clusters use kube-let certificate rotation, where the kube-let asks the ay-pee-eye server to renew its certificate automatically before it expires.

For the exam, the practical skills are, know where these files live, know that they have expiry dates, and know that kube-ay-dee-m can check and renew them. The mental model to keep is simple. Two authorities, one for the front end and one for et-see-dee, and every component carries a certificate that says who it is.
